Regression Project¶

Problem Statement¶

In foods, CODA (close of day availability) is one of the most important performance metrics. There are many departments and functions who are involved in the responsibility of the outcome of CODA. Previously there was no measure for the different functions to understand how their actions impacted CODA. A new measure was introduced to the business called Standards. The idea is, given all other variables stay constant the standard is the value supply chain must achieve. CODA previously was just measured against products performance last year, if a product has no history, it was viewed up against a similar product. Standards uses a more comprehensive process to calculate the target value. A couple steps used in the process are the following:

  • Previous four weeks’ worth of data on a rolling basis.
  • The use of data from similar products also.

Using regression, it is hoped the model can learn the standards value and then recreate them. My initial expectation is that categories with a more constant CODA value like “Confectionery”, “Beers & Spirits” and “Groceries” will have a more accurate recreated standards value. Categories with a less consistent CODA value will have a less accurate recreated standards value such as “Fruit”, “Food on the move” and “Poultry”.

Hypothesis¶

Null hypothesis:

There is no significant difference between the original standards and the recreated standards.

Alternative hypothesis:

There is a significant difference between the original standards and the recreated standards.

The significant level will be set at 0.05

Overview¶

The initial plan for the project is as follows:

  1. Source the data
  2. Explore & clean the data
  3. Prepare the data for analysis
  4. Analyse the data
  5. Evaluate the model
  6. Improve the model

Source the data¶

The data was sourced from a report called Horizon which was created by the food analytics team. The data is at product level but aggregated to different time periods. For a better CODA value, the last four weeks aggregation was selected. Initial thoughts about potential issues:

  • Since the last four weeks is used in calculating the original standards, could this result in perfect regression results.
  • As standards are calculated at day level, could an aggregation of the last four weeks cause the results to be less accurate as there would be 28 less data points for each product/metric combination.

Explore & clean the data¶

Initially the idea was to explore, clean and then prepare the data but due to issue while exploring It was decided to merge the exploring and the cleaning process into one.

Preparing the data¶

First thing we need to do is to split our dataset into test and training data. If we don't do this, then we can't effectively and reliably test our model. For our first model, we're only going to focus on two variables – CODA_STAND as our dependent, and CODA as our sole independent predictor.

In [304]:
# Create test and train datasets
# Create smaller datasets consisting of just our dependent and indepent variables
X = dataset2[["CODA"]] 
y = dataset2[["CODA_STAND"]]
# Double brackets allow us to keep the column headings
# Split the data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.25, random_state = 123)
# The test_size parameter means we can train with 75% of the data, and test on 25%
# The random_state parameter allows our work to be checked and replicated by other data scientists
In [305]:
# Check that the sizes match and that all is fine
print(X_train.shape, y_train.shape)
print(X_test.shape, y_test.shape)

This is the standard deviation of the residuals, and in this case its very small. The closer the value is to zero the better the quality of the estimator. This result should be expected because we saw previously that CODA explains 57% of the variance of the data.

Significance of the model¶

The p-value is less than 0.001, so given our significance level is 0.05 then we reject the null hypothesis, and therefore the model is statistically significant and explains 57% of the variance of CODA_STAND

To get an even better predictive model, we should use more than one variable.

Conclusion¶

After creating four different models we can conclude that our best model was model 4 which was a multi-regression model excluding the irrelevant predictors. It was the most accurate using the least predictors.

We also had to reject the null hypothesis for our original regression model using CODA as the 0.05>0.00 (SL>P-value). So, we must accept our alternative hypothesis that there is a significant difference between the original standards and the recreated standards. The difference was 0.07% which isn’t a big different but aggregated from product level to total business level could give a totally different value. The impact could be a coda stand too high showing the business to be underperforming when it’s not or a coda stand which is too low showing that the business is over preforming when it’s not. Next steps would have been to extract the model output and plug back into our horizon report to see how accurate the model is. Also fully understand the procedure of how coda stand is calculated and if there are other metrics, we can use to then build a very accurate model which can perfectly predict coda stand.
